VIRIDON NEW YORK INC. FORMULA RATE IMPLEMENTATION PROTOCOLS The formula rate template ("Template") and these formula rate implementation protocols ("Protocols") together comprise the filed rate ("Formula Rate") of Viridon New York Inc. ("VNY") for transmission revenue requirement determinations made in accordance with the New York Independent System Operator Inc. ("NYISO") Open Access Transmission Tariff ("NYISO Tariff"). VNY shall follow the instructions specified in the Formula Rate to calculate annually its net annual transmission revenue requirement ("Net Revenue Requirement"). The Net Revenue Requirement shall be determined for January 1 to December 31 of a given calendar year (the "Rate Year").1 The Formula Rate shall become effective for recovery of VNY's Net Revenue Requirement upon the effective date for incorporation into the NYISO Tariff through an appropriate filing with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC" or "Commission") under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act ("FPA"), 16 U.S.C. 824d. Section 1. Annual Projection a. No later than November 1 preceding the first Rate Year that VNY expects to recover Net Revenue Requirements under the NYISO Tariff, and each subsequent Rate Year thereafter, VNY shall determine its projected Net Revenue Requirement for the upcoming Rate Year in accordance with VNYs Formula Rate ("Annual Projection"). The Annual Projection shall include the True-Up Adjustment described and defined in Section 2 below, if applicable. b. Posting, Format, and Notice of Annual Projection. No later than November 1 preceding the first Rate Year, and each subsequent Rate Year, VNY shall cause an electronic version of the Annual Projection to be posted in both a Portable Document Format ("PDF") and fully-functioning Excel file on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List.2 VNY's posting shall include all inputs in sufficient detail to identify the components of VNY's projected Net Revenue Requirement, all inputs in sufficient detail to identify the components of VNY's Annual Projections, and explanations of the bases for the projections and input data. If the date for making such posting of the Annual Projection should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the posting shall be made no later than the next business day. VNY shall cause an electronic version of the Annual Projection to be posted in both a PDF and fully functioning Excel file at a publicly accessible location on NYISO's internet website. c. Accounting Changes. With respect to any Accounting Change (as that term is defined in Section 3.d.iii), VNY shall, in the Annual Projection, (i) identify any Accounting Changes; (ii) identify items included in the projected Net Revenue Requirement at an amount other than on a historic cost basis (e.g., fair value adjustments); (iii) identify any reorganization or merger transaction during the previous year and explain the effect of the accounting for such transaction(s) on inputs to the projected Net Revenue Requirement; and (iv) provide, for each item identified pursuant to Section 1.c.i - iii of these Protocols, a narrative explanation of the individual impact of such changes on the projected Net Revenue Requirement. d. Annual Projection Meeting. At least twenty (20) business days but no more than thirty (30) business days after November 1, VNY shall hold a stakeholder meeting with interested parties in order for VNY to explain its Annual Projection and to provide interested parties an opportunity to seek information and clarifications regarding the Annual Projection ("Annual Projection Meeting"). VNY shall cause to be posted on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List, the time, date, and location of the Annual Projection Meeting no fewer than seven (7) days prior to the Annual Projection Meeting, and VNY shall provide remote access to the Annual Projection Meeting to allow all interested parties the opportunity to remotely participate in such meetings. e. Revisions to the Annual Projection. To the extent VNY agrees to make changes in the Annual Projection for a given Rate Year, such revised Annual Projection shall be promptly posted at a publicly accessible location on NYISO's internet website, and e-mailed to the Service List. Changes posted prior to December 1 of the preceding Rate Year, or the next business day if December 1 is not a business day (or such later date as can be accommodated under NYISO's billing practices), shall be reflected in the Annual Projection collected during the Rate Year; changes posted after that date will be reflected, as appropriate, in the True-Up Adjustment for the Rate Year in the following year's Annual Update. f. Review and Challenge of the Annual Projection. The Annual Projection, including the True-Up Adjustment, for each Rate Year shall be subject to review, challenge, true-up and refunds or surcharges with interest at the applicable FERC rate pursuant to Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols. Section 2. Actual Net Revenue Requirement and True-Up Adjustment a. VNY will calculate the amount of under- or over-collection of its actual Net Revenue Requirement during the preceding Rate Year after the FERC Form No. 1 data for that Rate Year has been filed with the Commission. The True-Up Adjustment shall be the sum of the True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery as determined in Section 2(b) and the Interest on the True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery as determined in Section 2(c). b. Calculation of the True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery. To determine any over- or under-recovery ("True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery"), VNY's projected Net Revenue Requirement collected during the previous Rate Year3 will be compared to VNY's actual Net Revenue Requirement for the previous Rate Year. VNY shall calculate its actual Net Revenue Requirement in accordance with VNY's Formula Rate and based upon: (i) VNY's FERC Form No. 1 for that same Rate Year; (ii) any FERC orders specifically applicable to VNY's calculation of its Net Revenue Requirement; (iii) the books and records of VNY (which shall be maintained consistent with the FERC Uniform System of Accounts ("USofA")); (iv) FERC accounting policies and practices applicable to the calculation of Net Revenue Requirements under formula rates; and (v) any aspects of the NYISO Governing Documents4 that apply to the calculation of Net Revenue Requirements under individual transmission owner formula rates. c. Calculation of Interest. Interest on any True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery of the actual Net Revenue Requirement shall be calculated in accordance with Attachment 6 of the Formula Rate. d. Variance Analysis. VNY will include a variance analysis of, at minimum, actual Net Revenue Requirement components of rate base, operating and maintenance expenses, depreciation expense, taxes, return on rate base, and revenue credits as compared to the corresponding components in the projected Net Revenue Requirement that was calculated for the prior Rate Year with an explanation of material changes. Section 3. Annual Update a. No later than July 1 following each Rate Year, VNY shall calculate its actual Net Revenue Requirement and the True-Up Adjustment as described in Section 2 ("Annual Update") for such Rate Year. b. Posting and Notice of the Annual Update; Publication Date. No later than July 1 following each Rate Year, VNY shall cause such Annual Update, together with such other information described in this Section 3, to be posted in both a PDF and fully-functioning Excel format on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List. If the date for making the Annual Update posting should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the posting shall be made no later than the next business day. The date on which the last of the events listed in this Section 3.b occurs shall be that year's "Publication Date." c. Annual Update Meeting. At least twenty (20) business days but no more than thirty (30) business days after July 1, VNY shall hold a stakeholder meeting with interested parties in order for VNY to explain its Annual Update and to provide interested parties an opportunity to seek information and clarifications regarding the Annual Update ("Annual Update Meeting"). Notice of the Annual Update Meeting shall be provided via the Service List no less than seven (7) calendar days prior to the meeting. Remote access to Annual Update Meetings will be provided to allow all interested parties the opportunity to remotely participate in such meetings. d. The Annual Update for the Rate Year: i. Shall provide, via the Formula Rate worksheets, sufficiently detailed supporting documentation for data (and all adjustments thereto or allocations thereof) used in the Formula Rate that are not stated in the FERC Form No. 1;5 ii. Shall provide sufficient detail and sufficient explanation to enable interested parties to replicate the calculation of the Annual True-Up results from the FERC Form No. 1 and verify that each input to the Template is consistent with the requirements of the Formula Rate; iii. Shall identify: A. any change in accounting that affects inputs to the Template or the resulting charges billed under the Formula Rate ("Accounting Change"), including: I. the initial implementation of an accounting standard or policy; II. the initial implementation of accounting practices for unusual or unconventional items where FERC has not provided specific accounting direction; III. correction of errors and prior period adjustments that impact the True-Up Adjustment calculation; IV. the implementation of new estimation methods or policies that change prior estimates; and V. changes to income tax elections; B. any items included in the Annual True-Up at an amount other than on a historic cost basis (e.g., fair value adjustments); C. any reorganization or merger transaction during the previous year and an explanation of the effect of the accounting for such transaction(s) on inputs to the True-Up Adjustment; D. for each item identified pursuant to Sections 3.d.iii.A - C of these Protocols, the individual impact (in narrative format) of such changes on the True-Up Adjustment; iv. Shall not seek to modify the Formula Rate and shall not be subject to challenge by any Interested Party seeking to modify the Formula Rate (i.e., any modifications to the Formula Rate will require, as applicable, an FPA Section 205 or Section 206 filing or initiation of a Section 206 investigation); and, v. Shall include for the applicable Rate Year the following information related to affiliate cost allocation: (A) a detailed description of the methodologies used to allocate and directly assign costs between VNY and its affiliates by service category and function; and (B) the magnitude of such costs that have been allocated or directly assigned between VNY and each affiliate by service category or function. e. Stated Value Inputs. The following Formula Rate stated values shall be used in the Formula Rate until changed pursuant to an FPA Section 205 or Section 206 proceeding: (i) rate of return on common equity ("ROE"); (ii) Post-Employment Benefits other than Pensions ("PBOP") charges; and (iii) the depreciation and/or amortization rates as set forth in Attachment 6 to the Formula Rate template. VNY reserves the right to make a single-issue Section 205 filing to change (1) the depreciation rates stated in the Formula Rate Template based on a future depreciation study of assets owned by VNY or its affiliates located within NYISO, or (2) the PBOP value stated in the Formula Rate Template in the event that VNY's accounting records show a non-zero value. f. Review and Challenge of the Annual Update. The Annual Update shall be subject to review, challenge, true-up, and refunds or surcharges in accordance with the procedures set forth in Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols, including challenges concerning the prudence of any costs and expenditures included for recovery in the Annual Update; provided, however, that nothing in these Protocols is intended to modify the Commission's applicable precedent with respect to the burden of going forward or burden of proof under formula rates in such prudence challenges. g. Example - Timeline for 2025 Rate Year: On or before November 1, 2024, VNY will determine the projected Net Revenue Requirement for the 2025 Rate Year. VNY will post the Annual Projection for the 2025 Rate Year in accordance with Section 1 above. VNY will not determine a True-Up Adjustment or post an Annual Update on July 1, 2025 if no costs have been recovered under the Formula Rate during 2024. On or before July 1, 2026, VNY will post its Annual Update, consisting of the actual Net Revenue Requirement and True-Up Adjustment for the 2025 Rate Year determined pursuant to Section 2 above. Such True-Up Adjustment will be reflected in the Annual Projection of the Net Revenue Requirement for the 2027 Rate Year posted on or before November 1, 2026. The Annual Update posted July 1, 2026 will be subject to the customer review and challenge procedures described in Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols. Section 4. Annual Review Procedures The Annual Update and Annual Projection for each Rate Year shall be subject to the following review procedures ("Annual Review Procedures"): a. Information Requests and Responses i. Deadlines. Interested parties shall have one hundred and eighty (180) days following each annual Publication Date to serve reasonable information and document requests on VNY. VNY shall make a good faith effort to respond to information and document requests pertaining to the Annual Update and Annual Projection within fifteen (15) business days of receipt of such requests. VNY shall respond to all timely information and document requests by no later than two hundred and twenty (220) days following each annual Publication Date; provided, however, that VNY may reasonably extend the deadline for its own responses in the event that it extends the deadline for submission of information and document requests. If the date for submitting or responding to information and document requests should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the submissions or responses shall be due on the next business day. ii. Scope. Information requests shall be limited to what is necessary to determine: (A) the extent, effect, or impact of an Accounting Change; (B) whether the True-Up Adjustment fails to include data properly recorded in accordance with the Protocols; (C) the proper application of the Template and procedures in the Protocols; (D) the accuracy of data and consistency with the Formula Rate of the charges shown in the Annual Update or Annual Projection; (E) the prudence of the actual costs and expenditures; (F) the effect of any change to the underlying USofA account or applicable form; and (G) any other information that may reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation of the charge pursuant to the Formula Rate. iii. Limitation on Scope. Information requests shall not solicit information concerning costs or allocations where the costs or allocation methods have been determined to be appropriate by FERC in the context of prior VNY Annual Updates, except that such information requests shall be permitted if they (A) seek to determine if there has been a change in circumstances, (B) are in connection with corrections pursuant to Section 6 of these Protocols, or (C) relate to costs or allocations that have not previously been challenged and adjudicated by FERC. iv. Public Availability of Information Requests and Responses. VNY will promptly cause information requests received by VNY and VNY's responses thereto to be posted on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List; provided, however, that if responses to information and document requests include material deemed by VNY to be confidential information, such information will not be publicly posted but will be made available to requesting parties pursuant to a confidentiality agreement to be executed by VNY and the requesting party. v. Privilege. VNY shall not claim that responses to information and document requests provided pursuant to these protocols are subject to any settlement privilege in any subsequent proceeding addressing VNY's Annual Update or Annual Projection. vi. Disputes. To the extent VNY and any Interested Person(s) are unable to resolve disputes related to information requests submitted in accordance with these Annual Review Procedures, VNY or the Interested Person(s) may petition FERC to appoint an Administrative Law Judge as a discovery master to resolve the discovery dispute(s) in accordance with these Protocols and consistent with FERC's discovery rules. b. Informal Challenges i. Deadlines. Interested parties shall have the period of time from the Publication Date until the following March 1 ("Review Period") to review the calculations and to notify VNY in writing of any specific challenges to the Annual Update and Annual Projection ("Informal Challenge"), including challenges related to Accounting Changes; provided, however, that such Review Period may be extended with the written consent of VNY or by FERC order. If March 1 should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by the FERC, then Informal Challenges shall be due on the next business day. VNY shall make a good faith effort to respond to Informal Challenges within twenty (20) days of receipt of such challenge. VNY shall respond to all Informal Challenges no later than April 1; provided, however, that VNY may reasonably extend the deadline for its own responses in the event that it extends the Review Period. If April 1 should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then VNY's responses to Informal Challenges shall be due on the next business day. ii. Contents and Scope. An Interested Party submitting an Informal Challenge to VNY must specify the inputs, supporting explanations, allocations, calculations, or other information to which it objects, and provide an appropriate explanation and documents to support its challenge. A party may raise in an Informal Challenge all issues that may be necessary to determine: (A) the extent, effect, or impact of an Accounting Change; (B) whether the True-Up Adjustment fails to include data properly recorded in accordance with the Protocols; (C) the proper application of the Template and procedures in the Protocols; (D) the accuracy of data and consistency with the Formula Rate of the charges shown in the Annual Update; (E) the prudence of the actual costs and expenditures; (F) the effect of any change to the underlying USofA account or applicable form; and (G) any other information that may reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation of the charge pursuant to the Formula Rate. iii. Responses to Informal Challenges. In its responses, VNY shall notify the challenging party of the extent to which VNY agrees or disagrees with the challenge. If VNY disagrees with the Informal Challenge, its response shall include supporting documentation. iv. Public Availability of Informal Challenges and Responses. VNY shall promptly cause to be posted all Informal Challenges and VNY's responses to such Informal Challenges shall cause to be posted on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List; provided, however, that if Informal Challenges or VNY's responses to such Informal Challenges include material deemed by VNY to be confidential information, such challenges and responses will not be publicly posted but will be made available to requesting parties pursuant to a confidentiality agreement to be executed by VNY and the requesting party. v. Senior Representatives. VNY, and where applicable, NYISO, shall appoint a senior representative to work with the Interested Person(s) that submitted the Informal Challenge (or its representative) toward a resolution of the challenge. c. Accounting Changes i. Challenges Related to Accounting Changes. Informal or Formal Challenges (as described in Sections 4 and 5) related to Accounting Changes shall be treated in the same manner under these Protocols as other challenges to the Annual Update or Annual Projection. Failure to make an Informal Challenge with respect to an Accounting Change in an Annual Update or Annual Projection shall not act as a bar with respect to a Formal Challenge with respect to that Annual Update, nor shall such failure bar a subsequent Informal Challenge related to a subsequent Annual Update to the extent such Accounting Change affects the subsequent Annual Update. ii. Remedies. If a change made by VNY to its accounting policies, practices or procedures, or the application of the Formula Rate, is found by FERC to be unjust, unreasonable, or unduly discriminatory or preferential, then the calculation of the charges to be assessed during the Rate Year then under review, and the charges to be assessed during any subsequent Rate Years, including any True-Up Adjustments, shall not include such change, but shall include any remedy that may be prescribed by FERC in the exercise of its discretion as of the effective date of such remedy, to ensure that the Formula Rate continues to operate in a manner that is just, reasonable, and not unduly discriminatory or preferential. Section 5. Resolution of Challenges a. Deadlines. Any Interested Person(s) may file a challenge with FERC ("Formal Challenge") contesting some action or inaction by VNY with respect to the Annual Update or Annual Projection, and shall do so no later than May 15 following the end of the Review Period; provided, however, that such deadline may be extended with the written consent of VNY to continue efforts to resolve an issue or by FERC order. If May 15 should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then Formal Challenges shall be due on the next business day. b. Contents of Formal Challenges. Formal Challenges shall be filed pursuant to these protocols. All information and correspondence produced by VNY pursuant to these Protocols may be included in any Formal Challenge or other FERC proceeding relating to the Formula Rate, subject to any applicable confidentiality and Critical Energy Infrastructure Information restrictions. The Interested Person(s) filing such a Formal Challenge shall do all of the following: i. Clearly identify the action or inaction which is alleged to violate the Formula Rate (including the Template and/or these Protocols); ii. Explain how the action or inaction violates the Formula Rate (including the Template and/or these Protocols); iii. Set forth the business, commercial, economic, or other issues presented by the action or inaction as such relate to or affect the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge, including: (A) the extent or effect of an Accounting Change; (B) whether the True-Up Adjustment fails to include data properly recorded in accordance with the Protocols; (C) the proper application of the Template and procedures in the Protocols; (D) the accuracy of data and consistency with the Formula Rate of the charges shown in the Annual Update; (E) the prudence of the actual costs and expenditures; (F) the effect of any change to the underlying USofA account or applicable form; and (G) any other information that may reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation of the charge pursuant to the Formula Rate; iv. Make a good faith effort to quantify the financial impact or burden (if any) created for the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge as a result of the action or inaction; v. State whether the issues presented are pending in an existing Commission proceeding or a proceeding in any other forum in which the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge is a party, and, if so, provide an explanation as to why timely resolution cannot be achieved in that forum; vi. State the specific relief or remedy requested, including any request for stay or extension of time, and the basis for that relief; vii. Include all documents that support the facts in the Formal Challenge in possession of, or otherwise attainable by, the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge, including, but not limited to, contracts and affidavits; and, viii. State whether the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge utilized the Informal Challenge procedures described in these protocols to dispute the action or inaction raised by the Formal Challenge, and, if not, describe why not. c. Docketing and Service. Interested Person(s) shall submit Formal Challenges with the Commission in the same docket as the informational filing described in Section 7 and shall serve Formal Challenges on VNY by electronic service on the date of such filing in accordance with Section 385.2010(f)(3) of the Commission's regulations. d. Other Requirements. Failure to raise an issue in an Informal Challenge shall not bar an Interested Person from raising that issue in a Formal Challenge, provided the Interested Person submitted an Informal Challenge during the Review Period with respect to one or more other issues. e. Responses to Formal Challenges by VNY. Any response by VNY to a Formal Challenge must be submitted to FERC within thirty (30) calendar days of the date of the filing of the Formal Challenge, and shall be served on the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge and the Service List on the date of such filing. If such deadline should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then VNY's responses to Informal Challenges shall be due on the next business day. f. Burden. In any Formal Challenge proceeding concerning a given year's Annual Update (including corrections), Annual Projection, or Accounting Change(s), VNY shall demonstrate the justness and reasonableness of the rate resulting from its application of the Formula Rate by demonstrating that it has reasonably and accurately calculated the Annual Update and/or reasonably adopted and applied the Accounting Change. g. Reservation of Rights under FPA Sections 205 and 206. Except as specifically provided in these Protocols, nothing herein shall be deemed to limit in any way the right of VNY to file unilaterally, pursuant to Section 205 of the FPA and the regulations thereunder, an application seeking changes to the Formula Rate or to any of the stated values therein requiring a Section 205 filing under these Protocols (including, but not limited to, ROE and depreciation rates), or the right of any interested parties or the Commission to seek such changes pursuant to Section 206 of the FPA and the regulations thereunder. Section 6. Changes to Annual Updates a. If VNY determines or concedes under Sections 4 and/or 5 of these Protocols that corrections to the Annual Update are required (including but not limited to those requiring corrections to its FERC Form No. 1 or input data used for a Rate Year that would have affected the Annual Update for that Rate Year), VNY shall promptly cause a correction to the Annual Update to be posted on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List. b. Such corrections shall be reflected in the next Annual Update, with interest. Interest on any over- or under-recovery due to corrections for preceding True-Up Adjustments shall be calculated monthly on such over- or under-recovery from January 1 of the corrected Rate Year through December 31 of the Rate Year in which such over- or under-recovery is reflected ("Correction Period"). That is equivalent to two years interest applied to over- or under- collection. The applicable monthly interest rates for the Correction Period for an over-recovery or under-recovery shall be the annual interest rates for each month pursuant to 18 C.F.R. 35.19a divided by twelve (12) for each month from the beginning of the Correction Period through December 31 of the Rate Year immediately preceding the Rate Year in which such over-recovery is reflected. c. Such corrections shall be subject to review at the time they are made, and the corrected posting shall be followed by a review period ("Correction Review Period"), during which the scope of review shall be limited to the aspects of the Annual Update affected by the corrections. VNY and any Interested Person(s) shall work together in good faith to set a reasonable duration for such Correction Review Period and the deadlines for submission and/or responses to information and document requests, Informal Challenges, and Formal Challenges. Section 7. Informational Filing a. Deadline. VNY shall submit to FERC an informational filing ("Informational Filing"), in a newly established FERC docket, of its projected Net Revenue Requirement for a Rate Year, including the True-Up Adjustment determined during the preceding Annual Update, by April 15 of the Rate Year; provided, however, that VNY may delay the deadline for filing the Informational Update to account for any previous delays in the Review Period or deadline for submitting or responding to Informal Challenges. If April 15 should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the Informational Filing shall be due on the next business day. VNY will provide notification of the FERC Docket number for the Informational Filing directly to NYISO and to other parties through the Service List maintained by VNY. b. Contents. This Informational Filing must include the information that is reasonably necessary to determine: (i) that input data under the formula rate are properly recorded in any underlying workpapers; (ii) that VNY has properly applied the formula rate and these procedures; (iii) the accuracy of data and the consistency with the formula rate of the Net Revenue Requirement and rates under review; (iv) the extent of Accounting Changes that affect Formula Rate inputs; and (v) the reasonableness of projected costs. The Informational Filing must also describe any corrections or adjustments made during that period, and must describe all aspects of the Annual Update or its inputs that are the subject of an ongoing dispute under the Informal or Formal Challenge procedures. c. Challenges. Any challenges to the implementation of the Template must be made through the procedures described in Sections 4 and 5 of these protocols or in a separate complaint proceeding and must not be made in response to the Informational Filing. Section 8. Joint Meeting of Transmission Owners Each year VNY shall endeavor to coordinate with other transmission owners in the NYISO using formula rates to establish revenue requirements for recovery of the costs of transmission projects that utilize the same regional cost sharing mechanism and transmission owners that own inter-regional projects whose costs are allocated in part to NYISO members in order to arrange a joint informational meeting to enable all interested parties to understand how those transmission owners are implementing their formula rates for recovering the costs of such projects. 1 In the event VNY's initial projected Net Revenue Requirement is to be provided to NYISO after October 31 of the year preceding the first Rate Year, VNY will prepare an Annual Projection for the first Rate Year using the most recent information available, and, in the event of a partial Rate Year, reflecting VNY's Net Revenue Requirement only for the remaining months of the Rate Year. VNY shall cause the Annual Projection to be posted on the NYISO internet website, and distributed to the Service List, at least sixty (60) days prior to NYISO's anticipated inclusion of the projected VNY Net Revenue Requirement in the access charges developed pursuant to the NYISO Tariff. 2 As used in these protocols, "Service List" shall mean (i) the email list of the NYISO OATT Transmission Customers maintained by NYISO; (ii) any state regulatory agency with rate jurisdiction over a public utility located within the NYISO footprint; and (iii) any consumer advocate agency authorized by state law to review and contest the rates for any such public utility, provided such consumer advocate agency requests to be placed on the Service List and provides an email address to VNY. 3 If the initial use of the Formula Rate covers only part of a calendar year, the initial projected Net Revenue Requirement will be divided by the number of months the Formula Rate is in effect to calculate the monthly projected cost of service to be collected each month of the first year. Similarly, the actual Net Revenue Requirement will be divided by the number of months the rate is in effect to calculate the actual cost of service to be collected each month of the first year. The first True-Up Adjustment will compare the projected Net Revenue Requirement billed and the actual Net Revenue Requirement for that initial Rate Year. 4 NYISO Tariff Governing Documents include the NYISO Tariff, Bylaws, Criteria, and Membership Agreements. 5 It is intended that each input to the Formula Rate for purposes of determining the actual Net Revenue Requirement for a given Rate Year will be either taken directly from the FERC Form No. 1 or reconcilable to the FERC Form No. 1 by the application of clearly identified and supported information. If the referenced form is superseded, the successor form(s) shall be utilized and supplemented as necessary to provide equivalent information as that provided in the superseded form. If the referenced form is discontinued, equivalent information as that provided in the discontinued form shall be utilized. ---------------

amount other than on a historic cost basis (e.g., fair value adjustments); (iii) identify any

d. Annual Projection Meeting. At least twenty (20) business days but no more than thirty
(30) business days after November 1, VNY shall hold a stakeholder meeting with
interested parties in order for VNY to explain its Annual Projection and to provide
interested parties an opportunity to seek information and clarifications regarding the
Annual Projection (Annual Projection Meeting). VNY shall cause to be posted on the
NYISO internet website and OASIS (if available), and distributed to the Service List, the
time, date, and location of the Annual Projection Meeting within ten (10) days of the
posting of the Annual Projection and no fewer than seven (7) days prior to the Annual
Projection Meeting, and VNY shall provide remote access to the Annual Projection
Meeting to allow all interested parties the opportunity to remotely participate in such
meetings.
e. Revisions to the Annual Projection. To the extent VNY agrees to make changes in the
Annual Projection for a given Rate Year, such revised Annual Projection shall be
promptly posted at a publicly accessible location on NYISOs internet website and
OASIS (if available), and e-mailed to the Service List. Changes posted prior to December
1 of the preceding Rate Year, or the next business day if December 1 is not a business
day (or such later date as can be accommodated under NYISOs billing practices), shall
3
be reflected in the Annual Projection collected during the Rate Year; changes posted after
that date will be reflected, as appropriate, in the True-Up Adjustment for the Rate Year in
the following years Annual Update.
f. Review and Challenge of the Annual Projection. The Annual Projection, including the
True-Up Adjustment, for each Rate Year shall be subject to review, challenge, true-up
and refunds or surcharges with interest at the applicable FERC rate pursuant to Sections
4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols.
Section 2. Actual Net Revenue Requirement and True-Up Adjustment a. VNY will calculate the amount of under- or over-collection of its actual Net Revenue
Requirement during the preceding Rate Year after the FERC Form No. 1 data for that
Rate Year has been filed with the Commission. The True-Up Adjustment shall be the
sum of the True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery as determined in Section 2(b) and
the Interest on the True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery as determined in Section
2(c).
b. Calculation of the True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery. To determine any over- or
under-recovery (True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery), VNYs projected Net
4 Revenue Requirement collected during the previous Rate Year3F will be compared to
VNYs actual Net Revenue Requirement for the previous Rate Year. VNY shall calculate
its actual Net Revenue Requirement in accordance with VNYs Formula Rate and based
4 If the initial use of the Formula Rate covers only part of a calendar year, the initial projected Net Revenue Requirement will be divided by the number of months the Formula Rate is in effect to calculate the monthly projected cost of service to be collected each month of the first year. Similarly, the actual Net Revenue Requirement will be divided by the number of months the rate is in effect to calculate the actual cost of service to be collected each month of the first year. The first True-Up Adjustment will compare the projected Net Revenue Requirement billed and the actual Net Revenue Requirement for that initial Rate Year.
4
upon: (i) VNYs FERC Form No. 1 for that same Rate Year; (ii) any FERC orders
specifically applicable to VNYs calculation of its Net Revenue Requirement; (iii) the
books and records of VNY (which shall be maintained consistent with the FERC
Uniform System of Accounts (USofA)); (iv) FERC accounting policies and practices
applicable to the calculation of Net Revenue Requirements under formula rates; and (v)
5 any aspects of the NYISO Governing Documents4F that apply to the calculation of Net
Revenue Requirements under individual transmission owner formula rates.
c. Calculation of Interest. Interest on any True-Up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery of the
actual Net Revenue Requirement shall be calculated in accordance with Attachment 6 of
the Formula Rate.
d. Variance Analysis. VNY will include a variance analysis of, at minimum, actual Net
Revenue Requirement components of rate base, operating and maintenance expenses,
depreciation expense, taxes, return on rate base, and revenue credits as compared to the
corresponding components in the projected Net Revenue Requirement that was calculated
for the prior Rate Year with an explanation of material changes.
Section 3. Annual Update a. No later than July 1 following each Rate Year, VNY shall calculate its actual Net
Revenue Requirement and the True-Up Adjustment as described in Section 2 (Annual
Update) for such Rate Year.
b. Posting and Notice of the Annual Update; Publication Date. No later than July 1
following each Rate Year, VNY shall cause such Annual Update, together with such
5 NYISO Tariff Governing Documents include the NYISO Tariff, Bylaws, Criteria, and Membership Agreements.
5
other information described in this Section 3, to be posted in both a PDF and fully-
functioning Excel format on the NYISO internet website and OASIS site (if available),
and distributed to the Service List. If the date for making the Annual Update posting
should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the posting shall be
made no later than the next business day. The date on which the last of the events listed
in this Section 3.b occurs shall be that years Publication Date.
c. Annual Update Meeting. At least twenty (20) business days but no more than thirty (30)
business days after July 1, VNY shall hold a stakeholder meeting with interested parties
in order for VNY to explain its Annual Update and to provide interested parties an
opportunity to seek information and clarifications regarding the Annual Update (Annual
Update Meeting). Notice of the Annual Update Meeting shall be provided via the
Service List within ten (10) days of the posting of the Annual Update and no fewer than
seven (7) days prior to the Annual Update Meeting. Remote access to Annual Update
Meetings will be provided to allow all interested parties the opportunity to remotely
participate in such meetings.
d. The Annual Update for the Rate Year:
i. Shall provide, via the Formula Rate worksheets, sufficiently detailed supporting
documentation for data (and all adjustments thereto or allocations thereof) used in
6 the Formula Rate that are not stated in the FERC Form No. 1;5F
6 It is intended that each input to the Formula Rate for purposes of determining the actual Net Revenue Requirement for a given Rate Year will be either taken directly from the FERC Form No. 1 or reconcilable to the FERC Form No. 1 by the application of clearly identified and supported information. If the referenced form is superseded, the successor form(s) shall be utilized and supplemented as necessary to provide equivalent information as that provided in the superseded form. If the referenced form is discontinued, equivalent information as that provided in the discontinued form shall be utilized.
6
ii. Shall provide sufficient detail and sufficient explanation to enable interested
parties to replicate the calculation of the Annual True-Up results from the FERC
Form No. 1 and verify that each input to the Template is consistent with the
requirements of the Formula Rate;
iii. Shall identify:
A. any change in accounting that affects inputs to the Template or the
resulting charges billed under the Formula Rate (Accounting Change),
including:
I. the initial implementation of an accounting standard or policy;
II. the initial implementation of accounting practices for unusual or
unconventional items where FERC has not provided specific
accounting direction;
III. correction of errors and prior period adjustments that impact the
True-Up Adjustment calculation;
IV. the implementation of new estimation methods or policies that
change prior estimates; and
V. changes to income tax elections;
B. any items included in the Annual True-Up at an amount other than on a
historic cost basis (e.g., fair value adjustments);
C. any reorganization or merger transaction during the previous year and an
explanation of the effect of the accounting for such transaction(s) on
inputs to the True-Up Adjustment;
7
D. for each item identified pursuant to Sections 3.d.iii.A C of these
Protocols, the individual impact (in narrative format) of such changes on
the True-Up Adjustment;
iv. Shall not seek to modify the Formula Rate and shall not be subject to challenge by
any Interested Party seeking to modify the Formula Rate (i.e., any modifications
to the Formula Rate will require, as applicable, an FPA Section 205 or Section
206 filing or initiation of a Section 206 investigation); and,
v. Shall include for the applicable Rate Year the following information related to
affiliate cost allocation: (A) a detailed description of the methodologies used to
allocate and directly assign costs between VNY and its affiliates by service
category and function; and (B) the magnitude of such costs that have been
allocated or directly assigned between VNY and each affiliate by service category
or function.
e. Stated Value Inputs. The following Formula Rate stated values shall be used in the
Formula Rate until changed pursuant to an FPA Section 205 or Section 206 proceeding:
(i) rate of return on common equity (ROE); (ii) Post-Employment Benefits other than
Pensions (PBOP) charges; and (iii) the depreciation and/or amortization rates as set
forth in Attachment 6 to the Formula Rate template. VNY reserves the right to make a
single-issue Section 205 filing to change (1) the depreciation rates stated in the Formula
Rate Template based on a future depreciation study of assets owned by VNY or its
affiliates located within NYISO, or (2) the PBOP value stated in the Formula Rate
Template in the event that VNYs accounting records show a non-zero value. All parties
reserve the right to contest such filing(s). Nothing in these Protocols is intended to
8
modify the Commissions ability to determine whether such a single-issue filing is
consistent with the rate change standards under Section 205 on a case-by-case basis.
f. Review and Challenge of the Annual Update. The Annual Update shall be subject to
review, challenge, true-up, and refunds or surcharges in accordance with the procedures
set forth in Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols, including challenges concerning the
prudence of any costs and expenditures included for recovery in the Annual Update;
provided, however, that nothing in these Protocols is intended to modify the
Commissions applicable precedent with respect to the burden of going forward or
burden of proof under formula rates in such prudence challenges.
g. Example Timeline for 2025 Rate Year:
On or before November 1, 2024, VNY will determine the projected Net Revenue
Requirement for the 2025 Rate Year. VNY will post the Annual Projection for the 2025
Rate Year in accordance with Section 1 above. VNY will not determine a True-Up
Adjustment or post an Annual Update on July 1, 2025 if no costs have been recovered
under the Formula Rate during 2024.
On or before July 1, 2026, VNY will post its Annual Update, consisting of the actual Net
Revenue Requirement and True-Up Adjustment for the 2025 Rate Year determined
pursuant to Section 2 above. Such True-Up Adjustment will be reflected in the Annual
Projection of the Net Revenue Requirement for the 2027 Rate Year posted on or before
November 1, 2026. The Annual Update posted July 1, 2026 will be subject to the
customer review and challenge procedures described in Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these
Protocols.
Section 4. Annual Review Procedures
9
The Annual Update and Annual Projection for each Rate Year shall be subject to the
following review procedures (Annual Review Procedures):
a. Information Requests and Responses
i. Deadlines. Interested parties shall have one hundred and eighty (180) days
following each annual Publication Date to serve reasonable information and
document requests on VNY. VNY shall make a good faith effort to respond to
information and document requests pertaining to the Annual Update and Annual
Projection within fifteen (15) business days of receipt of such requests. VNY shall
respond to all timely information and document requests by no later than two
hundred and twenty (220) days following each annual Publication Date; provided,
however, that VNY may reasonably extend the deadline for its own responses in
the event that it extends the deadline for submission of information and document
requests. If the date for submitting or responding to information and document
requests should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the
submissions or responses shall be due on the next business day.
ii. Scope. Information requests shall be limited to what is necessary to determine:
(A) the extent, effect, or impact of an Accounting Change; (B) whether the True-
Up Adjustment fails to include data properly recorded in accordance with the
Protocols; (C) the proper application of the Template and procedures in the
Protocols; (D) the accuracy of data and consistency with the Formula Rate of the
charges shown in the Annual Update or Annual Projection; (E) the prudence of
the actual costs and expenditures, including information on procurement methods
and cost control methodologies; (F) the effect of any change to the underlying
10
USofA account or applicable form; and (G) any other information that may
reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation of the charge pursuant to the
Formula Rate.
iii. [Reserved]
iv. Public Availability of Information Requests and Responses. VNY will promptly
cause information requests received by VNY and VNYs responses thereto to be
posted on the NYISO internet website and OASIS (if available), and distributed to
the Service List; provided, however, that if responses to information and
document requests include material deemed by VNY to be confidential
information, such information will not be publicly posted but will be made
available to requesting parties pursuant to a confidentiality agreement to be
executed by VNY and the requesting party.
v. Privilege. VNY shall not claim that responses to information and document
requests provided pursuant to these protocols are subject to any settlement
privilege in any subsequent proceeding addressing VNYs Annual Update or
Annual Projection.
vi. Disputes. To the extent VNY and any Interested Person(s) are unable to resolve
disputes related to information requests submitted in accordance with these
Annual Review Procedures, VNY or the Interested Person(s) may petition FERC
to appoint an Administrative Law Judge as a discovery master to resolve the
discovery dispute(s) in accordance with these Protocols and consistent with
FERCs discovery rules.
b. Informal Challenges
11
i. Deadlines. Interested parties shall have the period of time from the Publication
Date until the following March 1 (Review Period) to review the calculations
and to notify VNY in writing of any specific challenges to the Annual Update and
Annual Projection (Informal Challenge), including challenges related to
Accounting Changes; provided, however, that such Review Period may be
extended with the written consent of VNY or by FERC order. If March 1 should
fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by the FERC, then Informal Challenges
shall be due on the next business day. VNY shall make a good faith effort to
respond to Informal Challenges within twenty (20) days of receipt of such
challenge. VNY shall respond to all Informal Challenges no later than April 1;
provided, however, that VNY may reasonably extend the deadline for its own
responses in the event that it extends the Review Period. If April 1 should fall on
a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then VNYs responses to Informal
Challenges shall be due on the next business day.
ii. Contents and Scope. An Interested Party submitting an Informal Challenge to
VNY must specify the inputs, supporting explanations, allocations, calculations,
or other information to which it objects, and provide an appropriate explanation
and documents to support its challenge. A party may raise in an Informal
Challenge all issues that may be necessary to determine: (A) the extent, effect, or
impact of an Accounting Change; (B) whether the True-Up Adjustment fails to
include data properly recorded in accordance with the Protocols; (C) the proper
application of the Template and procedures in the Protocols; (D) the accuracy of
data and consistency with the Formula Rate of the charges shown in the Annual
12
Update; (E) the prudence of the actual costs and expenditures; (F) the effect of
any change to the underlying USofA account or applicable form; and (G) any
other information that may reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation
of the charge pursuant to the Formula Rate.
iii. Responses to Informal Challenges. In its responses, VNY shall notify the
challenging party of the extent to which VNY agrees or disagrees with the
challenge. If VNY disagrees with the Informal Challenge, its response shall
include supporting documentation.
iv. Public Availability of Informal Challenges and Responses. VNY shall promptly
cause to be posted all Informal Challenges and VNYs responses to such Informal
Challenges shall cause to be posted on the NYISO internet website and OASIS (if
available), and distributed to the Service List; provided, however, that if Informal
Challenges or VNYs responses to such Informal Challenges include material
deemed by VNY to be confidential information, such challenges and responses
will not be publicly posted but will be made available to requesting parties
pursuant to a confidentiality agreement to be executed by VNY and the requesting
party.
v. Senior Representatives. VNY, and where applicable, NYISO, shall appoint a
senior representative to work with the Interested Person(s) that submitted the
Informal Challenge (or its representative) toward a resolution of the challenge.
c. Accounting Changes
i. Challenges Related to Accounting Changes. Informal or Formal Challenges (as
described in Sections 4 and 5) related to Accounting Changes shall be treated in
13
the same manner under these Protocols as other challenges to the Annual Update
or Annual Projection. Failure to make an Informal Challenge with respect to an
Accounting Change in an Annual Update or Annual Projection shall not act as a
bar with respect to a Formal Challenge with respect to that Annual Update, nor
shall such failure bar a subsequent Informal Challenge related to a subsequent
Annual Update to the extent such Accounting Change affects the subsequent
Annual Update.
ii. Remedies. If a change made by VNY to its accounting policies, practices or
procedures, or the application of the Formula Rate, is found by FERC to be
unjust, unreasonable, or unduly discriminatory or preferential, then the calculation
of the charges to be assessed during the Rate Year then under review, and the
charges to be assessed during any subsequent Rate Years, including any True-Up
Adjustments, shall not include such change, but shall include any remedy that
may be prescribed by FERC in the exercise of its discretion as of the effective
date of such remedy, to ensure that the Formula Rate continues to operate in a
manner that is just, reasonable, and not unduly discriminatory or preferential.
Section 5. Resolution of Challenges a. Deadlines. Any Interested Person(s) may file a challenge with FERC (Formal
Challenge) contesting some action or inaction by VNY with respect to the Annual
Update or Annual Projection, and shall do so no later than May 15 following the end of
the Review Period; provided, however, that such deadline may be extended with the
written consent of VNY to continue efforts to resolve an issue or by FERC order. If May
14
15 should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then Formal Challenges
shall be due on the next business day.
b. Contents of Formal Challenges. Formal Challenges shall be filed pursuant to these
protocols. All information and correspondence produced by VNY pursuant to these
Protocols may be included in any Formal Challenge or other FERC proceeding relating to
the Formula Rate, subject to any applicable confidentiality and Critical Energy
Infrastructure Information restrictions. The Interested Person(s) filing such a Formal
Challenge shall do all of the following:
i. Clearly identify the action or inaction which is alleged to violate the Formula Rate
(including the Template and/or these Protocols);
ii. Explain how the action or inaction violates the Formula Rate (including the
Template and/or these Protocols);
iii. Set forth the business, commercial, economic, or other issues presented by the
action or inaction as such relate to or affect the Interested Person(s) filing the
Formal Challenge, including: (A) the extent or effect of an Accounting Change;
(B) whether the True-Up Adjustment fails to include data properly recorded in
accordance with the Protocols; (C) the proper application of the Template and
procedures in the Protocols; (D) the accuracy of data and consistency with the
Formula Rate of the charges shown in the Annual Update; (E) the prudence of the
actual costs and expenditures; (F) the effect of any change to the underlying
USofA account or applicable form; and (G) any other information that may
reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation of the charge pursuant to the
Formula Rate;
15
iv. Make a good faith effort to quantify the financial impact or burden (if any)
created for the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge as a result of the
action or inaction;
v. State whether the issues presented are pending in an existing Commission
proceeding or a proceeding in any other forum in which the Interested Person(s)
filing the Formal Challenge is a party, and, if so, provide an explanation as to why
timely resolution cannot be achieved in that forum;
vi. State the specific relief or remedy requested, including any request for stay or
extension of time, and the basis for that relief;
vii. Include all documents that support the facts in the Formal Challenge in possession
of, or otherwise attainable by, the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal
Challenge, including, but not limited to, contracts and affidavits; and,
viii. State whether the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal Challenge utilized the
Informal Challenge procedures described in these protocols to dispute the action
or inaction raised by the Formal Challenge, and, if not, describe why not.
c. Docketing and Service. Interested Person(s) shall submit Formal Challenges with the
Commission in the same docket as the informational filing described in Section 7 and
shall serve Formal Challenges on VNY by electronic service on the date of such filing in
accordance with Section 385.2010(f)(3) of the Commissions regulations.
d. Other Requirements. Failure to raise an issue in an Informal Challenge shall not bar an
Interested Person from raising any issue(s) in a Formal Challenge, provided the Interested
Person submitted an Informal Challenge during the Review Period with respect to any
issue(s).
16
e. Responses to Formal Challenges by VNY. Any response by VNY to a Formal Challenge
must be submitted to FERC within thirty (30) calendar days of the date of the filing of the
Formal Challenge, and shall be served on the Interested Person(s) filing the Formal
Challenge and the Service List on the date of such filing. If such deadline should fall on a
weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then VNYs responses to Informal
Challenges shall be due on the next business day.
f. Burden. In any Formal Challenge proceeding concerning a given years Annual Update
(including corrections), Annual Projection, or Accounting Change(s), VNY shall
demonstrate the justness and reasonableness of the rate resulting from its application of
the Formula Rate by demonstrating that it has reasonably and accurately calculated the
Annual Update and/or reasonably adopted and applied the Accounting Change.
g. Reservation of Rights under FPA Sections 205 and 206. Except as specifically provided
in these Protocols, nothing herein shall be deemed to limit in any way the right of VNY
to file unilaterally, pursuant to Section 205 of the FPA and the regulations thereunder, an
application seeking changes to the Formula Rate or to any of the stated values therein
requiring a Section 205 filing under these Protocols (including, but not limited to, ROE
and depreciation rates), or the right of any interested parties or the Commission to seek
such changes pursuant to Section 206 of the FPA and the regulations thereunder.
Section 6. Changes to Annual Updates a. If VNY determines or concedes under Sections 4 and/or 5 of these Protocols that
corrections to the Annual Update are required (including but not limited to those
requiring corrections to its FERC Form No. 1 or input data used for a Rate Year that
would have affected the Annual Update for that Rate Year), VNY shall promptly cause a
17
correction to the Annual Update to be posted on the NYISO internet website and OASIS
(if available), and distributed to the Service List.
b. Such corrections shall be reflected in the next Annual Update, with interest. Interest on
any over- or under-recovery due to corrections for preceding True-Up Adjustments shall
be calculated monthly on such over- or under-recovery from January 1 of the corrected
Rate Year through December 31 of the Rate Year in which such over- or under-recovery
is reflected (Correction Period). That is equivalent to two years interest applied to over-
or under- collection. The applicable monthly interest rates for the Correction Period for
an over-recovery or under-recovery shall be the annual interest rates for each month
pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a divided by twelve (12) for each month from the beginning
of the Correction Period through December 31 of the Rate Year immediately preceding
the Rate Year in which such over-recovery is reflected.
c. Such corrections shall be subject to review at the time they are made, and the corrected
posting shall be followed by a review period (Correction Review Period), during which
the scope of review shall be limited to the aspects of the Annual Update affected by the
corrections. VNY and any Interested Person(s) shall work together in good faith to set a
reasonable duration for such Correction Review Period and the deadlines for submission
and/or responses to information and document requests, Informal Challenges, and Formal
Challenges.
Section 7. Informational Filing a. Deadline. VNY shall submit to FERC an informational filing (Informational Filing), in
a newly established FERC docket, of its projected Net Revenue Requirement for a Rate
Year, including the True-Up Adjustment determined during the preceding Annual
18
Update, by April 15 of the Rate Year; provided, however, that VNY may delay the
deadline for filing the Informational Update to account for any previous delays in the
Review Period or deadline for submitting or responding to Informal Challenges. If April
15 should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the Informational
Filing shall be due on the next business day. VNY will provide notification of the FERC
Docket number for the Informational Filing directly to NYISO and to other parties
through the Service List maintained by VNY and will post the docket number to OASIS
within five (5) days of the filing.
b. Contents. This Informational Filing must include the information that is reasonably
necessary to determine: (i) that input data under the formula rate are properly recorded in
any underlying workpapers; (ii) that VNY has properly applied the formula rate and these
procedures; (iii) the accuracy of data and the consistency with the formula rate of the Net
Revenue Requirement and rates under review; (iv) the extent of Accounting Changes that
affect Formula Rate inputs; and (v) the reasonableness of projected costs. It will also
include a workable data-populated template and underlying work papers in native format
with all formulas and links intact. The Informational Filing must also describe any
corrections or adjustments made during that period, and must describe all aspects of the
Annual Update or its inputs that are the subject of an ongoing dispute under the Informal
or Formal Challenge procedures.
c. Challenges. Any challenges to the implementation of the Template must be made through
the procedures described in Sections 4 and 5 of these protocols or in a separate complaint
proceeding and must not be made in response to the Informational Filing.
Section 8. Joint Meeting of Transmission Owners
19
Each year VNY shall endeavor to coordinate with other transmission owners in the
NYISO using formula rates to establish revenue requirements for recovery of the costs of
transmission projects that utilize the same regional cost sharing mechanism and transmission
owners that own inter-regional projects whose costs are allocated in part to NYISO members
in order to arrange a joint informational meeting to enable all interested parties to understand
how those transmission owners are implementing their formula rates for recovering the costs
of such projects.
Section 9. Competitive Project Adjustments
a. For transmission development projects assigned to VNY as a result of the NYISO competitive project
sponsor process, VNY may agree with NYISO to apply cost concessions that will reduce the annual
revenue requirement on a project-specific basis from what would otherwise be produced by the
Formula Rate. The adjustment to the revenue requirement resulting from agreed-to cost concessions
is referred go as the Competitive Project Adjustment (CPA). Any CPA will reduce the annual
revenue requirement for the relevant transmission project, i.e., the CPA will not cause the annual
revenue requirement for a project to exceed the annual revenue requirement calculated without the
CPA.
b. For any competitively assigned project for which there are agreed-to cost concessions, VNY will
provide to Interested Parties any project selection report presented by the NYISO for approval by the
NYISO Board, and any elements of the Development Agreement specifying project pricing
commitments or concessions, in connection with each VNY Annual Update.
c. The CPA for each competitive project will be reported in Attachment 12 of the Template. VNY will
provide detailed support for the calculation of the CPA for each project based on the applicable
agreed-to cost commitments. The CPA for a competitive project will be calculated by (1) populating
the Template with project-specific cost inputs to determine the project-specific revenue requirement
20
without concessions, (2) populating the Template with project-specific cost inputs applying any
agreed-to concessions to determine the project cost revenue requirement with concessions, and (3)
determining the CPA for the project as the difference between the project revenue requirement
before concessions and the project revenue requirement after concessions. The project CPA is
recorded on Att. 10 of the VNY template, and the sum of project CPAs (if VNY has more than one
project) is the input to Attachment A, Page 3, Line 48 in the VNY Template.
